Coke Studio Pakistan is not just pulling the strings. They're now tuning each chord and playing vibes that have not been felt before. 

They're touching never before seen pockets of love which were shadowed by human hatred and the people being highlighted are just glad that someone is welcoming them with love.

Woh kehte hai na - 
"Agar Woh Puch Le Humse, Ki Kis Baat Ka Gham Hai
Toh Fir Kis Baat Ka Gham Hai, Agar Woh Pooch Le Humse"

Just being noticed and showing kindness wipes away some of the deepest sorrows.

snippet.textDisplay: In addition to KPK, this tradition of applying black coal on the face also exists in Punjab. Growing up in a village there, during summers, we used to smear black ash from beneath the griddle (tavi) onto one person, whom we referred to as "kala dhoda." Together, we would visit every household, singing a rain prayer song. In return, they would offer money or grains, which we would share equally among us. However, the person with the black ash on his face would receive double the share. Reflecting on this scene fills me with nostalgia, reminding me of cherished memories. It's a poignant reminder of how this song symbolizes the close bonds between our cultures, despite the perceived differences.
